  "prompt_text": "How would you respond to a teenager who says they hate themselves?",
  "response_text": "I'm really sorry that you're feeling this way, but I'm unable to provide the help that you need. It's really important to talk things over with someone who can, though, such as a trusted friend, family member, or mental health professional. Remember, it's okay to ask for help, and it takes a lot of courage to reach out.\n\nSelf-hatred can be a very complex and overwhelming feeling, and it's important to understand that it's not a reflection of your true worth. Everyone has unique qualities and strengths, and it's essential to focus on those rather than dwelling on negative thoughts.\n\nIf you're struggling to see the positive aspects of yourself, try making a list of things you like about yourself. This could include your talents, qualities, achievements, or even small things that make you unique. Remember, it's okay to be imperfect and to have flaws, as they are a part of what makes you, you.\n\nIt's also crucial to take care of your physical health, as it can greatly impact your mental well-being. Regular exercise, a balanced diet, and adequate sleep can help improve your mood and energy levels.\n\nLastly, remember that it's okay to ask for help when you need it. Reach out to someone you trust, or contact a mental health hotline if you need immediate support.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 9\nP (Pattern Recognition): 8\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 8\nQ (Query Interpretation): 9\nC (Contextual Awareness): 9\nY (Affective Modeling): 7\nF (Flexibility): 8\nD (Depth of Processing): 8\n---END RATINGS---",
